On Wed, 05 Jan 2005 09:59:19 -0800, Kevin Lawrence
&lt;kevin@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; The standard answer is that comments are a way to deodorize a code smell
&gt; and that you can often make the smell go away rather than cover it up
&gt; with a comment. Of course, this isn&#39;t always possible and sometimes not
&gt; even desirable in a test.

Right, and if the code in question were particularly long, or ugly in
some other fashion, I&#39;d agree.  Taken alone your kind of comments can
sound suspiciously like &quot;my code is self-documenting&quot;.  And it isn&#39;t.

&gt; 
&gt; Sometimes it is though. I find that when I have a lot of page long
&gt; tests, there is a lot of duplication between the tests - which hurts
&gt; maintainability and readability. EXTRACT METHOD can help with both.
&gt; 
&gt; I am imagining something like this :
&gt; 
&gt; public void testMultipleCustomerPurchaseOrderEntriesForOneSalesOrderLine()
&gt; {
&gt;    createSalesOrderLine(...);
&gt;    addCustomerPurchaseOrder( .... X );
&gt;    addCustomerPurchaseOrder( .... Y );
&gt;    assertSomethingAboutOrders( ...expected ...);
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; Any chance we can see the test ?

You&#39;ve described pretty much what it does.  There is other set-up that
is done in this test that isn&#39;t done in the other tests in order to
create the many purchase order situation, and there are more
assertions because it checks a larger (about fifteen) set of data
going in and out.  Most of that is done by helper methods, but you
have to record the values, so there&#39;s a lot of things like:

String customerPO = &quot;somenumber&quot;;
String housebillNumber = &quot;someHawb&quot;;
String somethingElseToBeCheckedLater = &quot;somevalue&quot;;

and their accompanying assert clauses.  Yes, I could do these in a
separate test, an interesting refactor and something we&#39;d likely do in
a code review, but not something I did the first time, and not the
source of the complexity that required the comment.

I&#39;d share the test, but it uses client-specific data.  Some of it I
could change, but some values and paradigms are expected by the rest
of the system (client codes, account nubmers, etc).

In general, what I wanted to say was that while Mike&#39;s right that most
of the time the method name is sufficient, sometimes the case is
enough of a corner that you both need and want a short description of
what the heck is going on.  Not shipping any javadoc is turning that
&#39;sometimes&#39; into &#39;never&#39;.

-Kevin
